As a writer who will actually be doing this in my next story. I will say that you should generally stick to one or another in the same story. If you want to change up the structure, make sure you justify it either with a change of perspective, or a dramatic shift in the story, etc. Going from Anon in greentext to first person Anon in prose, for example is too jarring and it feels like it's being done just for the sake of doing it.

Honestly, keeping some of the animalistic traits adds to the immersion, much like having human characters from different tribes behave differently does.

What's more, humans have ingrained behaviors just like any other animal. Think about our inherent disgust with the smell of feces / rotten stuff, our fascination with fire, and reactions to dominant or submissive behavior.

If you've got a character who's closer to an animal, particularly a species of known quantity, it's only natural to expect to see some of the behavior traits carried over. This can be extremely helpful in giving the reader an idea of the sort of character to expect. It also gives the writer (or artist) something to work with, either by accentuating traits or by subverting them (often to the social detriment of the character).
